The Great Macroeconomic Discrepancy
PARIS – "Global expansion has reached its peak," warns the OECD in its latest economic outlook, and performance could suffer if downside risks materialize.
The party is not over yet: it is expected that global growth will continue in 2019 and 2020 – albeit at a slower pace.
Yet economic forecasters are notoriously bad at recognizing macroeconomic turning points, and the future economic trajectory is difficult to predict.
Potential stumbling blocks abound: more aggressive monetary policy tightening, especially in the United States; further escalation of protectionism; a Chinese economic landing harder than expected; and a return of tensions in the eurozone, triggered by concerns about the fate of Italian state finances.
All this or each of these developments could intensify the downturn that has already set in.
A recession in the US would be frustrating for President Donald Trump, who is looking ahead to his re-election in 2020, although such a development would not be inconsistent with known patterns.
Officially, the expansion began in June 2009, and with a duration until July 2019, it would have been the longest such phase in the economic history of the USA.
Unemployment is at its lowest level since the 1960s.
Under these conditions, implementing the economic policy measures of the Trump administration, consisting of massive tax cuts and spending increases – essentially a stimulus package comparable to that of 2009, which was aimed at averting a looming depression – would be economically nonsensical.
With that, the Federal Reserve only has two options: either it raises interest rates drastically to offset the poorly timed fiscal and monetary stimuli, or it capitulates.
This irresponsible game of chicken between US budget and monetary authorities increases the risk of instability in the rest of the world given the global impact of the US interest rate cycle.
A global recession would come too early for those countries whose recovery has either been delayed or weak or both.
An extreme example is Greece, where growth only started in 2017 and unemployment still stands at nearly 20 percent.
But Greece is not alone.
In Italy, per capita GDP is no higher than in the mid-1990s.
And in Spain, France, South Korea, and other countries, unemployment is still significantly above pre-crisis levels.
The challenge is to re-employ long-term unemployed workers, who face the risk of skill erosion.
To avoid a lasting socio-economic damage, these countries need faster growth.
A promising international situation alone cannot solve their problems, but it would help maximize the benefits of national reforms.
The other extreme is the German labor market, which currently presents itself much better than in 2007.
In the western states, full employment prevails and economic growth is increasingly dependent on immigration: in 2017, the net inflow – no refugees, but immigrants from other European countries – was around 400,000 people.
In Japan, the UK, and Poland, the recovery was also characterized by the creation of many jobs.
Citizens complain about income, inequality, or rising home prices, but not about a lack of jobs.
Ten years ago, the crisis hit almost all developed economies simultaneously.
<s>They are neither structurally nor cyclically aligned.
<s>This is certainly concerning, as the impending cooling of the world economy comes at a time of increasing political fragility.
<s>Trust in governments and institutions of political decision-making is – understandably – extremely low.
<s>Collective economic mismanagement would only further erode this trust and fuel the already rising economic nationalism.
<s>What should be done now?
<s>The list of tasks begins at home. In many countries where the labor market is still out of balance, national measures are needed to strengthen economic potential and improve access to jobs.
<s>Even with an unemployment rate of 9 percent and President Emmanuel Macron's reforms, employers in France report a skills shortage.
<s>To change this, comprehensive measures in the education field as well as support for mobility, incentives for job acceptance, and the opening of protected sectors are necessary.
<s>This is already happening.
<s>In Italy, on the other hand, the ruling coalition has initiated an economic program and at the same time proposed measures to reduce labor force participation.
Among these are the repeal of the 2011 pension reform and the introduction of a "citizen's income", which in case of insufficient planning or implementation will lead to fewer people seeking employment.
This political inconsistency and Italy's deviation from the European Union's budget rules are the real cause for concern.
The second priority is to achieve a risk equilibrium.
For some time now, there has been a political debate between hawks and doves, with the former warning that the purchases of assets by central banks as well as near-zero interest rates could foster financial instability and inflation risks. The greatest concern of the doves, however, is deflation.
Both are certainly real, although there is more reason to be concerned about deflation.
Real estate bubbles can be dampened with regulatory measures, such as capping the ratio of loan amount to property value or to income.
Regarding inflation, forecasts are regularly falsified.
Wages have so far reacted slowly to falling unemployment.
There is justified fear of a possible sudden rise, but after so many years of undershooting inflation, this risk can be taken into account.
The collective costs of a temporary overshoot of inflation pale in comparison to those of an premature onset of recession, which leads to lasting damage and a political backlash against economic orthodoxy.
The third priority, international coordination, is farthest from being achieved, especially in the eurozone, where the European Central Bank pursues a uniform monetary policy for different economies.
The standard recipe would involve the ECB targeting an average inflation rate, and relying on fine-tuning of the macroeconomic course through national fiscal policies.
But precisely the countries that would need more growth are those that have no fiscal policy space available.
Neither Greece nor Italy, let alone Spain or France, can seriously consider a substantial economic stimulus program right now.
Without the possibility of cross-border transfers (which are also not provided for in the recent agreement between France and Germany on a mini-eurozone budget), this is another reason why the ECB should be bolder.
<s>This would leave the governments of the overheating countries the task of cooling their economies with fiscal measures, while the governments of the still struggling economies would have the task of tapping their economic potential.
<s>There are numerous reasons to doubt that this is possible.
<s>But it is the task of political decision-makers to steer risks, even if today's risks are unlike the usual ones.
<s>The resilience of the world economic system is at stake.
<s>Despite favorable conditions, initial cracks are appearing.
Es gilt zu verhindern, dass daraus Brüche werden.
